    "There's a story I heard from an installer that perfectly captures why window replacement matters more than most people realize. A family in our town had original windows from 1988. The parents had been talking about replacing them for over a decade. Always next year. Always after the kitchen remodel, after the kids' braces, after the vacation. Then their 14-year-old daughter started having recurring headaches and respiratory issues. Doctor visits, allergy tests, nothing conclusive. Finally, an environmental consultant found mold — significant mold — growing inside the window frames and behind the drywall beneath three windows where chronic condensation had been feeding moisture into the wall cavity for years. The remediation cost: $11,400. The window replacement cost: $13,200. Total: $24,600. If they had replaced the windows five years earlier — before the mold established itself — the total cost would have been roughly $12,000. By waiting, they didn't save $12,000. They spent an additional $12,600. And their daughter breathed mold spores for years. The windows you're thinking about replacing 'someday' might be creating a health hazard right now. The financial argument is compelling. The comfort argument is compelling. But the health argument? That's the one that should make you pick up the phone today. Not next month. Not next year. Today.",
